<subSubSection pageId="122" pageNumber="880" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="122.[2065,2659,1767,2196]" pageId="122" pageNumber="880">
<collectingRegion box="[2066,2113,1847,1880]" country="South Sudan" name="Lakes" pageId="122" pageNumber="880">See</collectingRegion>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[2125,2263,1847,1880]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Lasiurus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="122" pageNumber="880" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="egregius">L. egregius</taxonomicName>
. Based on allozyme studies, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. S. Miller" authorityYear="1931" box="[2066,2222,1886,1919]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Lasiurus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="122" pageNumber="880" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="degelidus">L. degelidus</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rhoads" baseAuthorityYear="1895" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Lasiurus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="122" pageNumber="880" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="seminolus">L. seminolus</taxonomicName>
, but cladistic analyses ofalleles suggest they differ enough to be considered distinct species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. S. Miller" authorityYear="1931" box="[2269,2515,2005,2038]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Lasiurus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="122" pageNumber="880" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="degelidus">Lasiurus degelidus</taxonomicName>
is in the Red Bat group. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
